This information will be included in the decision on the measures to be implemented, such as planting pastures and how best to care for the forests of bats and other associated species.
The flagermus population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has sunk considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and construction work that affect breeding sites and restriction of habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, the same with fly paper and certain chemically treated building materials as well as attacks from huts.
Flag mice are not blind.
But because of their nightly hunting habits, they have more use for their ears than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echo localization to find insects and obstacles on the road when flying.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
