Update on algae bloom: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Commission for Fisheries and Wildlife (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spotty blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County, suggesting reduced concentrations.
A bloom of red algae extends around 210 km along the coast, from the north of Pinellas to the south of Lee County.
There are spots around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than last week.
Red algae has also been observed in Pasco County.
Mean concentrations have been reported at or off the coast of Pinellas County last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Lee County and low.
There is still irritation in the airways of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
No irritation was reported in the airways in the northwest of Florida during the last week.
